  <h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Strategies to Enable Effective Implementation</h3>

<p>In this section, reflect on how you can implement this competency in your daily work. To help with this process, review these <strong>five implementation strategies</strong>.</p>
<h3>Tiered Approach</h3>
<p>These implementation strategies follow a <strong>tiered approach of widening circles of influence</strong>. Through this approach, MCH leaders utilize resources and tools to activate change within their organization, which in turn incorporates partners through its systems of influence. Together, changes may be implemented to affect specific target populations and the MCH community in general. </p>
<p><img src="../../images/spheres-of-influence.png" alt="Implementation Model" width="1956" height="700"/></p>
<h3>Implementation Strategies</h3>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> <strong>Self-Reflection Strategy. </strong>How to advance yourself as an MCH leader.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Advance Yourself as an MCH Leader</strong>. Identify your personal strengths and areas of growth by taking 5 minutes to register/log-in to the MCH Navigator's <a href="../../assessment/index.php">Self-Assessment</a> and answer questions related to Competency 5: Communication.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>Information Strategy. </strong>How to find and use tools to help you.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Find and Use Tools to Help You</strong>.  The National Center for Education in Maternal and Child Health's (NCEMCH) has compiled a <a href="https://www.mchlibrary.org/professionals/communication.php">resource brief</a> highlighting the variety of approaches and innovations used to advance communication in maternal and child health. Contents include a selection of websites, materials from the MCH Knowledge Base, and trainings from the MCH Navigator.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-university"></i> <strong>Organizational Strategy. </strong>How to activate your organization.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Activate Your Organization</strong>. Does your organization have an up-to-date plan for communicating in the event of a public health emergency? Learn how a health agency, a health professions association, and a school of public health collaborated to create a <a href="https://drexel.edu/~/media/Files/dornsife/CPHRC/AAP%20Toolkit.ashx?la=en">communications toolkit</a> for public health emergencies that impact children. Resources such as checklists, practice templates and guidelines, and flowcharts for pediatric practices, schools, and child care programs are included. <br>
  </p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>Systems Strategy. </strong>How to incorporate partners.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Incorporate Partners</strong>. Many individuals do not receive the services they need or qualify for due to systemic deficits in communication and information systems. This <a href="https://www.healthit.gov/sites/default/files/9-5-federalhealthitstratplanfinal_0.pdf">strategic plan</a> outlines strategies to advance a national communications infrastructure that supports health, safety, and care delivery. The plan's success will be measured by monitoring a set of proxy indicators including the percent of individuals who experienced one or more gaps in health information when seeking care. Learn more about who has committed to implementing specific strategies and how the plan's strategies connect to other strategic initiatives. Do you recognize opportunities for partnership and alignment?</p>
</div><button class="accordion"><i class="mch-globe"></i> <strong>Community Strategy. </strong>How to engage your communities.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How  to  Engage Your Communities</strong>. Many federal, state, and local agencies; national and state organizations and associations; and foundations are integrating social media into their communication efforts – from developing governance to determine which channels best meet their objectives; to creating a social media strategy; to providing access to health information when, where, and how users want it. A variety of tools can be used to reinforce and personalize messages, reach new audiences, and build a communication infrastructure based on open information exchange. In an effort to provide real-time access to emerging public health issues, the Association of Maternal and Child Health Programs and the National Center for Education in Maternal and Child Health partnered to aggregate <a href="https://www.mchlibrary.org/toolkits/states-twitter.php">Social Media in the States</a>. Follow the multi-state Twitter feed, or use <a href="https://www.mchlibrary.org/toolkits/states-social-media-map.php">the map</a> to learn about other state social media outlets. Join the conversation! </p>
</div>
</div>  

      
<h2><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> 5.3.2 PRACTICE</h2>
	  <div class="evidenceBorder">
	  <h3><i class="mch-bookmarks"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-reflect.jpg" alt="Image of Thought Bubble" class="right ppic" />REFLECT. Staying Motivated</h3>
	  <p>As you work through your growth in this competency, it's important to stay motivated. Here are some tips to help you maintain focus and productivity along the way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>          <strong>Set tiny goals</strong>. 
        If you find yourself procrastinating, set tiny goals.            The objective is to get started, which is always the hardest part of getting the work done. For example, your goal for the next 15 minutes might be to read and summarize a small section of new information rather than cover a whole topic area.          </li>
        <li><strong>Never memorize information without first understanding it</strong>. 
          The human brain is designed to process information, not to store information like it&rsquo;s a hard drive. This is why meaningful learning is far more effective than rote learning.            Meaningful learning occurs when you understand the information and make sense of it. If you don&rsquo;t understand the material after reading through it several times, don&rsquo;t be afraid to ask for assistance.</li>
        <li><strong>Explain the concept to someone else</strong>. 
          An excellent way to master a complex topic is to explain it to someone else.          Through the act of explaining the topic to another person, you&rsquo;ll get a better understanding of the topic.          If you can&rsquo;t explain the concept in a simple way, it means that you probably haven&rsquo;t mastered the concept yet.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><img src="../../images/mch-smart-motivation-5.jpeg" width="1024" height="512" alt="Motivational image" /> </p>
